04311nam a22006375i 9780674029668DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20212001mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740296687 a10.4159/97806740296682doi  a(DE-B1597)574477  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHM821 -- C64 2000eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a303.3721 aCohen, G. A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIf You're an Egalitarian, How Come You’re So Rich? /cG. A. Cohen. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIf You’re an Egalitarian, How Come You’re So Rich -- tProspectus -- t1 Paradoxes of Conviction -- t2 Politics and Religion in a Montreal Communist Jewish Childhood -- t3 The Development of Socialism from Utopia to Science -- t4 Hegel in Marx: The Obstetric Motif in the Marxist Conception of Revolution -- t5 The Opium of the People: God in Hegel, Feuerbach, and Marx -- t6 Equality: From Fact to Norm -- t7 Ways That Bad Things Can Be Good: A Lighter Look at the Problem of Evil -- t8 Justice, Incentives, and Selfishness -- t9 Where the Action Is: On the Site of Distributive Justice -- t10 Political Philosophy and Personal Behavior -- tEnvoi -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tCredits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book presents G. A. Cohen's Gifford Lectures, delivered at the University of Edinburgh in 1996. Focusing on Marxism and Rawlsian liberalism, Cohen draws a connection between these thought systems and the choices that shape a person's life. In the case of Marxism, the relevant life is his own: a communist upbringing in the 1940s in Montreal, which induced a belief in a strongly socialist egalitarian doctrine. The narrative of Cohen's reckoning with that inheritance develops through a series of sophisticated engagements with the central questions of social and political philosophy. In the case of Rawlsian doctrine, Cohen looks to people's lives in general. He argues that egalitarian justice is not only, as Rawlsian liberalism teaches, a matter of rules that define the structure of society, but also a matter of personal attitude and choice. Personal attitude and choice are, moreover, the stuff of which social structure itself is made. Those truths have not informed political philosophy as much as they should, and Cohen's focus on them brings political philosophy closer to moral philosophy, and to the Judeo-Christian ethical tradition, than it has recently been.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674029668423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674029668.jpg  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK